<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Helvetica, sans-serif">
I've heard the idea fronted before, but I have yet to hear what's so terribly wrong with it.  Imagine the spell:<P>Illusion.  23, 34, 45. Mind line.  Gives the target the appearance of the caster.  Breaks under the same conditions as stealth, otherwise 10/20/30 mins.<P>Whether you change the name overhead, or the information you get when clicking, can be tested.  I think the spell is usefull without either, but may be better with both. Also, the spell doesn't fool mobs.  It's strictly a player thing.<P>With that established, does this sound too powerful, or too hard to implement?  What I like about it is that it gives charm added utility - if you lose a pet, you grab anything nearby and cast illusion on it.  At least you have a doppleganger then.<P>-Jeff
</FONT>
